'''Cleopatra VI Tryphaena''' ({{lang-el|Κλεοπάτρα Τρύφαινα}}) was an Egyptian Ptolemaic queen. She may be identical with [[Cleopatra V of Egypt|Cleopatra V]].

There were at least two, perhaps three Ptolemaic women called ''Cleopatra Tryphaena'':

==Tryphaena, daughter of Ptolemy VIII Physcon and Cleopatra III==
[[Tryphaena]] was a sister of [[Ptolemy IX Lathyros]], [[Ptolemy X Alexander I]], [[Cleopatra IV of Egypt|Cleopatra IV]] and [[Cleopatra Selene of Syria|Cleopatra Selene]].<ref name="DH"/><ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.sfagn.info/information/kritt.html|title=Numismatic Evidence for a New Seleucid King: Seleucus (VII) Philometor|author=Brian Kritt|journal=The Celator|volume=16|issue=4|date=April 2002|postscript=.|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928103357/http://www.sfagn.info/information/kritt.html|archivedate=2007-09-28|df=}}</ref> If this ''Tryphaena'' also bore the name ''Cleopatra'', has not been attested. This Tryphaena may have been born in early 140 or 141 BC. She married [[Antiochus VIII Grypus]], king of [[Seleucid Empire|Syria]], in 124 BC, and bore him five sons: [[Seleucus VI Epiphanes]], the twin [[Antiochus XI Epiphanes]] and [[Philip I Philadelphus]], [[Demetrius III Eucaerus]], and [[Antiochus XII Dionysus]]. The couple also had a daughter called [[Laodice VII Thea|Laodice]].  Tryphaena was killed in [[Antioch]] (Greek: Αντιόχεια), capital of Syria, by [[Antiochus IX Cyzicenus]], as a revenge for his own wife's (Cleopatra IV) death by the orders of her sister Tryphaena (in 111 BC).<ref>{{citation | author = Justin | title = Epitoma historiarum Philippicarum Pompei Trogi | pages = 39.2.3, 39.3.4–12 | authorlink = Justin (historian)}}, our only source for these events.</ref>

==Cleopatra V Tryphaena, wife of Ptolemy XII Auletes==
[[Cleopatra V of Egypt|Cleopatra V Tryphaena]] was a Queen of Egypt until her mysterious disappearance from the records in 69 BC. If, as some scholars believe, her disappearance is attributable to her death, then it must be assumed that she had a daughter also called ''Cleopatra Tryphaena''.<ref name="DH"/>

==Cleopatra Tryphaena, daughter of Cleopatra V and Ptolemy XII Auletes==
She is called ''Cleopatra VI Tryphaena'' by some modern historians<ref name = "Tyldesley" /> and she would have been an older sister of the famous [[Cleopatra VII]].<ref name="DH">Dodson, Aidan and Hilton, Dyan. The Complete Royal Families of Ancient Egypt. Thames & Hudson. 2004. {{ISBN|0-500-05128-3}}</ref> If so, her birth year would correctly be c. 75 BC. The only instance she is mentioned in historical sources is by [[Porphyry (philosopher)|Porphyry]]. He says that when Ptolemy XII fled to Rome to avoid an uprising in Alexandria against him (in 58 BC), [[Berenice IV of Egypt|Berenice IV]] took control of [[Ptolemaic Egypt]] and ruled alongside her sister, Cleopatra Tryphaena.<ref>[[Porphyry (philosopher)|Porphyry]], cited by [[Felix Jacoby]], ''[[Fragmente der griechischen Historiker]]'', no. 260 F 2, 14</ref><ref>{{citation | author = [[Eusebius of Caesarea]] | title = ''Chronicle'' | page = 167 | publisher = Schoene | url = http://www.attalus.org/translate/eusebius1.html#167}}.</ref>  Strabo, however, states that Ptolemy had three daughters, of whom only the eldest (Berenice) was legitimate.<ref>{{citation | author = [[Strabo]] | title = Geographica | page = 17.1.11 | url = http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/17A2*.html#1.11 | publisher = University of Chicago}}.</ref>  This suggests that the Cleopatra Tryphaena referred to by Porphyry may have been Ptolemy's wife, not his daughter. Some, though not all, experts now identify Cleopatra VI with [[Cleopatra V of Egypt]], Ptolemy's wife.<ref name= "Tyldesley">{{citation | last = Tyldesley | first = Joyce | title = Thames & Hudson | year = 2006 | page = 200 | isbn = 0-500-05145-3}}.</ref>

